This was our first visit to Tio's; I had the two tamale plate with pork and red sauce; another tried the chimichanga plate and the third member of our group had the (3) taco plate and he ordered the chips and salsa. First off, the chips are excellent, warm, puffy and a hint of salt... 5 stars! The salsa is okay, no cilantro (lucky for diner #2), but there isn't much depth of flavor (3.5 stars). The tamales were very good to me, another thought they were heavy...he wanted a lighter, fluffier texture. The pork filling and the red sauce were very good and I gave them 4+ stars. I heard positive comments from my two tablemates about their dishes so it was a thumbs up, foodwise. There are two tables that can accommodate 6 people, plus counter seating for 4 - 6 more (I recall). The owner is nice and friendly and we now have two choices for Mexican food in downtown Honolulu. We'll be back! Recommended!

I found this gem on Door Dash and I’m glad I did. I got my job absolutely obsessed with this place and now, finally, my husband. We’re from Chicago & I can proudly say this place by far has the best Mexican food on the island - PERIOD. The people working there are also phenomenal. I recommend the Chimichangas and the red tamales. A guy there brought out a Chile Relleno for us to try and my husbands eyes rolled to the back of his head.. he loved it. Their salsa tastes so authentic and their carne asada/chorizo are out of this world. I can go on and on... love this place so much! Wish it was closer to Wahiawa.

O.M.G. Thank the HEAVENS for Tio's!!!! We moved here about 5 months ago and have been DYING for some decent Mexican food.  Being a native of Denver I brought as many bags of New Mexican ground red chile and fresh roasted green chile that I could carry.....WE RAN OUT!!!!  Searching Honolulu, Kailua, Kaneohe, Kapolei...etc....etc.....I heard about Tio's from a friend at work that knew I was from Denver.  Let me tell you.....when I walked through the door I knew I was at my new FAVORITE Mexican restaurant.  Tio's taste just like back home in Colorado and they even know how to make a mean green and red chile!!!!  We are heading back to Denver for a visit so I will be bringing an entire suitcase of "Mexican Provisions" back that I can't get here on Oahu but I will also be visiting Tio's at least once or twice a week when I don't have time to cook!!!!! YOU ROCK TIO'S......and believe me....I WILL RECCOMEND YOU TO EVERYONE I KNOW!!!!

Service was ok but the spanish rice tasted of  to much vegetable oil   the chili had way to much flour inside and the beans were dry had no flavor.Not authentic New Mexican food at all .My wife and I hope they fix the problem with the brownish lettuce they use as garnish.New Mexico is Known for there red n green chili and this doesn't taste like it.Also the Indian taco comes with a red chili sauce type salsa not green and ground beef n beans so I can tell that this place isn't authentic new Mexican what so ever.For these prices we can tell there putting forth the bare minimum of effort and that's why we won't return.However we were glad to see they had a real new Mexican guy back there helping Ray out  very friendly it's to bad the owner isn't more authentic in what he does maybe he should take tips from the little guy from New Mexico he seemed to know alot but stated this is how the boss does it? We gave it a shot ,we may return

Last week I got the chorizo breakfast burrito and my BF and I split both the New Mexico Red and Santa Fe Green tamales. I also bought a dozen tamales to eat for breakfast throughout the week. The breakfast burrito is only $4 and it's my new favorite cheap eats in the Chinatown area. And, I thought the dozen tamales would be given to me frozen but to my surprise, they were fresh so I took them home and froze what I wasn't going to eat immediately. Today, I came back for a breakfast burrito but they stop serving them at 10:30...I was bummed but it was the opportunity to try something different so I got a Carne Asada Chimichanga ($11.50). It comes stuffed with rice and beans but it's also smothered - which isn't my preference, since it loses the yummy fried crispiness in the sauce - but it's my fault for not reading the menu closely. Overall, it was tasty but when I go back tomorrow (yes, i do love it here!), I'm ordering the breakfast burrito...and I'm going to try a vegetarian tamale. I'll probably order another dozen of them.  Tips: - Street parking, bring change - Look for their specials, which is printed and taped to the menu. Last week it was Stacked Enchiladas (my BF explained it as "enchilada lasagna") and today it was Indian taco - It's a small space - 1 table that seats 4, 1 table that seats 2, and bar seating with a couple of stools facing out at Nuuanu St. Both times I went have been on the weekend and there was seating available. They seem to get a steady stream of to-go orders.
